Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Suresh Lokiah¶

Investigation Overview¶

This exercise investigates the Prosper Loan dataset through Visualization to find patterns and correlation of Loans, Borrower, Lender to maximize the LenderYield.

The dataset was methodically analyzed using a variety of plot types to explore different relationships in the dataset. The findings were documented as 'Notes' after each plot or analysis. Some of the analysis were further drilled-downed to explore patterns.

The goal of the analysis is

  1. Evaluate the current scenario for Loans, Lenders
  2. Provide insights to Lender for earning higher Yields.

(The resulting report in slides was peer-reviewed and improved).

Dataset Overview¶

The Dataset conist of 113937 rows , 81 columns. The features in the dataset are organized as Loan Listing, Loan, Borrower Demographics, Borrower Credit Information, Investor and Loan ChargeOff.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset is made up of 113,937 rows and 81 columns. The features in the dataset has information about the Loan, Prosper, Investors and Borrowers.

Below are how the features from the dataset that can be categorized as:

  • Loan Listing: ListingKey, ListingNumber, ListingCreationDate, Term, LoanStatus, CreditGrade, ListingCategory, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, PercentFunded. ProsperRating(Numeric), ProsperRating(Alpha), ProsperScore,

  • Loan - LoanKey, LoanNumber, LoanCurrentDaysDelinquent, LoanFirstDefaultedCycleNumber, LoanMonthsSinceOrigination, LoanOriginalAmount, LoanOriginationDate, LoanOriginationQuarter, MonthlyLoanPayment, Investors, ClosedDate, InvestmentFromFriendsCount, InvestmentFromFriendsAmount

  • Borrower Demographics - MemberKey, BorrowerState, Occupation, Recommendations, EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, IsBorrowerHomeowner, CurrentlyInGroup, GroupKey, TotalProsperLoans, TotalProsperPaymentsBilled, OnTimeProsperPayments, ProsperPaymentsLessThanOneMonthLate, ProsperPaymentsOneMonthPlusLate, ProsperPrincipalBorrowed, ProsperPrincipalOutstanding

  • Borrower Credit information - DateCreditPulled, CreditScoreRangeLower, CreditScoreRangeUpper, FirstRecordedCreditLine, CurrentCreditLines, OpenCreditLines, TotalCreditLinespast7years, OpenRevolvingAccounts, OpenRevolvingMonthlyPayment, InquiriesLast6Months, TotalInquiries, CurrentDelinquencies, AmountDelinquent, DelinquenciesLast7Years, PublicRecordsLast10Years, PublicRecordsLast12Months, RevolvingCreditBalance, BankcardUtilization, AvailableBankcardCredit, TotalTrades, TradesNeverDelinquent, TradesOpenedLast6Months, DebtToIncomeRatio, IncomeRange, IncomeVerifiable, , ScorexChangeAtTimeOfListing, StatedMonthlyIncome

  • Investor: LenderYield, EstimatedEffectiveYield, EstimatedLoss EstimatedReturn, EstimatedLoss, EstimatedReturn, Investors,

  • Loan ChargeOff: LP_CustomerPayments, LP_CustomerPrincipalPayments, LP_InterestandFees, LP_ServiceFees, LP_CollectionFees, LP_GrossPrincipalLoss, LP_NetPrincipalLoss, LP_NonPrincipalRecoverypayments.

Here is the complete feature definition:

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1gDyi_L4UvIrLTEC6Wri5nbaMmkGmLQBk-Yx3z0XDEtI/edit

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

From each of the above category we like to understand

Listing

  1. LoanStatus distribution across listings
  2. Loan Term distribution for the listings
  3. What are the Popular ListingCategory
  4. Do ProsperRating exist pre 2009 and how does is coorelate with CreditRating
  5. Correlation between PropserRating(Numeric) and PropserRating(Alpha)
  6. ProsperRating to PropserScore(after 2009) Loan
  7. What types of loans are the investors funding (and which ones are not popular)
  8. Average number of investors for each loan
  9. Are there multiple borrowers for each loan
  10. Number of times the loan was funded by Friends Borrower Demographics
  11. Which States the borrowers come from.
  12. What occupation they hold
  13. What is the strength of repayment based on EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration.
  14. How many Borrowers belong to a group(groupkey)
  15. What percentage of people have recommendations
  16. Number of borrowers that have prosper loan before (and what is their status)
  17. Are borrower with multiple loan likely to default on other loans
  18. Who are good borrowers (who have borrowed before and payed-off) Borrower Credit
  19. What loans are high credit line borrowers looking for.
  20. Compare high earners/credit with Low earners/credit for Loan amount
  21. Study percentage of high worth customers in various stages of loan repayment. (default, deleinquent)
  22. Compare the low worth customers Investors
  23. How many times an investor has participated in the marketplace
  24. How much was his/her return
  25. How much was their Loss (LP)

From above, of all the areas of interest that can be explored with the data here is our Goal

Goal

The main goal we are going to focus on is to understand the Loan characterstics that investors must consider to have higher returns.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

To answer the above question, we must focus on features related to the Loan,Borrower, Lender and specifically these features:

ListingCreationDate, ListingCategory, LoanOriginalAmount, EstimatedReturn, LoanStatus, Term, CreditGrade, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, BorrowerState, Occupation, Recommendations, ProsperScore, LenderYield

CreditGrade and ProsperRating(Alpha) ==> RiskScore¶

Both CreditGrade and ProsperRating(Alpha) would mean the same for a loan i.e. the RiskScore of the loan.

So lets ensure that ALL the listings have this RiskScore.

In [7]:
df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].count()
Out[7]:
84853
In [8]:
## Are there any rows where these 2 columns have missing values.

print("Rows likely having null in BOTH CreditGrade and ProsperRating (Alpha) :  ",  df.shape[0] -  (df.CreditGrade.count() + df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].count()))
print()

Rows likely having null in BOTH CreditGrade and ProsperRating (Alpha) :   131
In [9]:
## So, Drop the rows have nulls in both CreditScore and PropserScore 
df = df[df.CreditGrade.notna() | df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].notna()]
print(df.shape)

## Now create a new Column - RiskScore from CreditGrade and ProsperScore
df['RiskScore'] = None
df.RiskScore=np.where(df.CreditGrade.notna() == True, df.CreditGrade, df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'])

(113806, 83)

Notes¶

  • The final count of cleaned-up rows for RiskScore is 113806.

## Lets see the Good and, (Potentially) Bad Loan

## Good Category Loan values
good_cat = ['Current', 'Completed']

good_loan = bad_loan = 0

## Plot
plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])
plt.title("Distribution by LoanStatus",fontsize=15 )
value_counts = df.LoanStatus.value_counts()
sb.countplot(data=df, y=df.LoanStatus, color=sb.color_palette()[0], order=value_counts.index);
plt.xlabel("Count of Loans")

#print(value_counts)
total = value_counts.values.sum()
for i in range(len(value_counts)):
    #idx = value_counts[i]
    count = value_counts[i]
    if value_counts.index[i] in good_cat:
        good_loan += count
    else:
        bad_loan += count
        
    #print(ListingCategory_Alpha[i], idx)
    #pct = str(math.ceil((count * 100)/total)) + "%"
    x = count + 2000
    plt.text(x, i,  count, ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10)


## Print Summary
good_loan_pct = math.ceil((good_loan * 100)/total)
bad_loan_pct = math.ceil((bad_loan * 100)/total)

print()


print("Good Loan = " + str(good_loan) + " (" + str(good_loan_pct) + "%)")
print(" Bad Loan = " + str(bad_loan)  + " (" + str(bad_loan_pct)  + "%)")

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶
ListingCreationDate, ListingCategory, LoanOriginalAmount, EstimatedReturn, LoanStatus, Term, CreditGrade, IncomeRange, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, BorrowerState, Occupation, Recommendations, ProsperScore,LenderYield variables were as expected except for the unusal distributions as mentioned below.




Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶
    

  • The 'ListingCreationDate - Distribution by Year and Month' shows a deep drop in count for Year 2009.  Upon further reviewing the variable definitions,  we noticed significance to 2009  and the month of July in regards to EstimatedReturn.  So we created 'df2009' dataframe to study the 'EstimatedReturns' for Loans after July 2009
    

    • 

  • The 'RiskScore' for the Loan was developed by merging 'CreditGrade' and 'ProsperRating(Alpha)', during the process we discovered about 131 rows where both the values were NA. So we updated the dataframe df (line 10) to ignore these rows.
    

    • 

  • About 27 rows seems to have greater number of recommendations than normal. Hence we tried to see if the borrower had good 'CreditScoreRangeLower'or 'IincomeRange' and, both these did not offer conclusive evidence for this. Further analysis could be done to narrow down the reason for this.
    

    • 

  • 'EmploymentStatusDuration' shows the 700+ months of employment, which does not appear to be accurate So we will drop it from further using this field.
    

    •
